  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Malta's Nomad Residence Permit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You need €3,500/month (€42,000/year) from professional activities—employment, freelancing, or business income. Passive income (dividends, rental, interest) does not count. You must also show contracts guaranteeing €17,500 over the next 5 months.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why does Malta require €100,000 health insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Malta wants to ensure nomads can cover significant medical expenses without burdening the public system. The €100,000 minimum for EU/UK/Malta coverage ensures comprehensive protection. This is higher than most countries require and effectively mandates full international health insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I renew the permit and stay more than 4 years?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Nomad Residence Permit can be renewed 3 times (1 year initial + 3 renewals = 4 years maximum). After 4 years, you cannot renew further and must leave or switch to a different visa category. The NRP does not lead to permanent residency.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the 5-month minimum stay requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          To renew your permit, you must spend at least 5 cumulative months per year physically in Malta. This doesn't need to be consecutive—you can travel and return. But if you spend more than 7 months outside Malta, you won't qualify for renewal.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Malta expensive to live in?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Malta is moderate to expensive by EU standards—more than Portugal or Eastern Europe, less than London or Switzerland. Expect €2,000-4,000/month for comfortable living including rent and insurance. The English environment and 4-year duration may justify the premium for many nomads.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work for Maltese clients on this visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The Nomad Residence Permit is exclusively for remote work serving foreign (non-Maltese) clients or employers. Providing services to Malta-based companies or individuals makes you ineligible. All income must come from outside Malta.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

